Others (Vulg. Aeth. Luther) give it an active sense, ⁴ God is not one who tempts to evil.' The latter interpretation would make the next clause (πειράζει δέ) mere tautology, and it has now no defenders. It seems to me that the case is equally strong against the former interpretation. The meaning of the rare word ἀπείραστος must be determined from the general force of πειράζω 111 the N.T., and especially from the following clause, which is evidently intended to be its exact correlative in the active voice (ἀπείρασ- τοςι πειράζει δὲ αὐτός).
